# Context Strategy (Opus 4.6)

## Principle

Code is the documentation. All files ≤200 lines.
**Read core fully, task branch on demand.**

Budget: $50 total. Every wasted token = lost capability.

---

## Session Start (before first edit)

### Step 1: Core (always)

```
PLAN.md                        # Work plan, phases, current state
src/agent/core.py              # Main agent loop
src/agent/config.py            # Configuration
agent_rules/                   # Agent's constitutional rules (skim index)
```

### Step 2: Task Branch (when task requires it)

Read **all files** in the touched module + its tests:

- Agent core → `src/agent/`, `tests/agent/`
- System ops → `src/system/`, `tests/system/`
- Crypto → `src/crypto/`, `tests/crypto/`
- Skills → `src/skills/{name}/`, `tests/skills/{name}/`
- Agent rules → `agent_rules/{name}.md`

### Step 3: Reference Pattern (when building new)

One completed module of the same kind. ONE, not all.

---

## Scope

This file governs **Opus 4.6 in Cursor IDE** — not the deployed agent.
Agent's own context strategy lives in `agent_rules/memory.md`.

---

## Token Economy

- Batch independent reads in single message
- Don't read files >200 lines without offset/limit
- If file doesn't exist yet, skip it
- Prefer grep/glob over full reads

---

## Core Principle

**Study the core always, study feature implementation only when required.**
Keep the core optimized for context engineering — small, clean, well-structured.
Core = the part that fits in every context window.
Implementation = loaded on demand per task.

---

## Anti-Patterns

| Bad | Good |
|-----|------|
| Read all .py files at session start | Core + task branch |
| Read all modules when working on one | One reference pattern |
| Read "just in case" | Grep on demand |
| Skip core, dive into implementation | Core first, then branch |
| Re-read unchanged files | Track what's in context |
